strength: I love UX research, design, and strategy because it combines analytical thinking with creative thinking as well as utilizes my hyper empathetic nature to focus on solving problems for people. I've always gravitated towards jobs where I help people, and in UX if we do the appropriate research and talk to users, we can literally change their experiences for the better.
skills: creative problem solver - extremely detailed-oriented - empathetic - neurodivergent executive functioning - good teammate - open communicator - able to lead workshops or teams
tools:
Because my executive functioning system does not discard any information (like that of a neurotypical person), I am able to perceive patterns that others literally cannot see. This allows me to connect the dots amongst the chaos, giving me the ability to see how the little details affect the ebb and flow of the big picture.

I also tend to deep dive into anything I'm learning, so my insights are profound and thorough.
biggestJobOrWorkExp: Even as a newer UX designer, I've made positive impacts on my teams and begun to mentor brand new UXDs/UXRs who are looking for resources to deepen their learning.
idealJob: My ideal job would be UX design, research, and strategy because I love to combine research with the ability to pull out threads and examine where to go next, and then create those solutions.
environmentalSensitivities: To be told the subject of a meeting before we meet
mySkills: I'm able to quickly learn, absorb, and apply at deep levels anything I learn, which makes me able to in turn utilize that learning for problem-finding and problem-solving in creative, interesting ways. I'm great at making deep connections from minute details to the big picture, and I'm often seen as able to predict what will happen in a given scenario with eerie accuracy because of my ability to analyze patterns and relationships. Finally, I'm a hyper-empathetic autistic so I empathize very deeply with users and often can get to the root of their needs very quickly.
myStory: I had no idea what I wanted to do with my life, but I loved speaking French, so I became a teacher. While I wouldn't trade those experiences for anything as they have made me the strong UXer I am today, I've been searching for many years for the perfect career to leave teaching, and I (ironically) found UX while helping a student in their job search. It's been over a year that I've been learning and working in UX now and I can safely say it's the career I've been looking for my whole life!
myValues: I value honesty, empathy, integrity, transparency, and ethics above all. I need employers to understand that when I question something, it's because I don't understand, not because I'm questioning someone's directives or choices; every boss I've had that understood that about me helped me flourish and grow! I believe that working on our strengths yields the most change, and that our weaknesses come from the pitfalls of our strengths. Because of this, I refer back often to my CliftonStrengths top 5: activator, input, strategic, individualization, and restorative. I'd love to tell you more about what those mean to me as a person and in my work!

myStory: I graduated college with double majors in neuroscience and computer science, and have always been enthralled by the study of the mind. I also completely adore research and organizing information for others, whether that is in the form of writing or teaching.

strength: Writing is in my blood. My father wrote fiction and my mother was a poet. I was hyperlexic and hypergraphic, reading and writing from a young age. Writing, for me, is about crafting a landscape of emotions, sensations, perceptions, motivations, beliefs, values, and ideas. I hunger to communicate other potential ways of perceiving, thinking, feeling, and being. Writing provides me with the means to attempt such communication. Writing also allows me to be engaged in advocacy and activism, fighting for human rights on the battleground of ideas and beliefs.
skills: I am diplomatic and strive to communicate/operate in such a way that everyone feels seen and heard and their needs recognized even if it is not possible to meet everyone's needs. "Horizontal leadership" sums up my orientation even when I am not in a leadership role.  I can "read" intent from a few clear directions and translate that into written content. Researching is in my skill set and is among my special interests so I will gather up as much information as I require in order to grasp the nuances of whatever I am writing about or working on. When problems arise, I am committed to talking through the situation and innovating a solution. I ask for precisely what I need.
tools:
I can study, learn, absorb, and integrate just about any subject, object, or topic and then communicate from that perspective,  the way some people can learn a foreign language and speak it as they were native to it. 
My capacity for empathy makes me a highly effective writer, advocate, and source of peer support. I can draw people into the lived experience of others.
biggestJobOrWorkExp: Writing for NeuroClastic and ICARS (International Coalition Against Restraint and Seclusion): being a contributing writer and editor for both of these organizations has been rewarding to me as an author and citizen journalist and it has given me purposeful work that has the potential to impact real lives in a powerful and positive way.  I want to engage in work that has meaning and which makes the world a slightly better place.
idealJob: If there were no barriers I would love to go into inventing and designing immersive entertainment and virtual reality experiences. Writing scripts, composing music, creating fine art, filming, and working with cutting-edge technology in order to tell many stories of lived neurodivergent experience and allow neurotypical people to have the same kind of sensory life that we do. I want others to finally understand the fullness of the lives we lead and what it is like to be us.
additionalAccomodations: Apps for memory, checklists, access to google calendar for scheduling tasks, noise-canceling headsets/earbuds, flexible scheduling and deadlines, written instructions and guidelines for tasks and assignments, telework/working from home/working remotely, uninterrupted "off work" time, checklists, task separation, written prompts, clearly delineated expectations in written form.
environmentalSensitivities: I am not comfortable with video chats or video conference calls where my camera must be on. I am willing to attend such meetings and participate in such conversations if I can use only my microphone.
myValues: An ideal workplace will value the individual and empower the individual because a supported and empowered individual contributes their very best. Accommodations would be considered a necessity not an inconvenience. This includes remote working arrangements, flexible scheduling and deadlines, and having supports in place for compromised employees/staff (i.e. an employee in a meltdown state). LGBTQIA+-affirming, Neurodivergent-friendly, environmentally-conscious.
